{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t# Conversation Ledger\n2\t\n3\tDurable, attributable records of visible coding-agent conversations, stored in\n4\tyour repository as git notes.\n5\t\n6\t`cledger` (also installed as `conversation-ledger`) is a small standalone\n7\tutility in the unix tradition: it appends immutable JSONL evidence events to\n8\t`refs/notes/conversation-ledger`, anchored to the commit you were on when the\n9\tconversation happened. Records ride the commit DAG — merge a branch and its\n10\tconversations come along — never touch your working tree or `git status`, and\n11\tride your normal `git push`/`git fetch` via an auto-installed, scan-gated\n12\tpre-push hook and fetch refspec (or explicitly, via `cledger sync`).\n13\t\n14\tConversation Ledger is the neutral foundation of a small ecosystem:\n15\t\n16\t- `conversation-ledger` stores normalized, provenance-preserving conversation evidence.\n17\t- `turnbridge` records and transfers visible conversations between coding CLIs.\n18\t- `intent-recall` later retrieves evidence to help agents reason about original and superseded intent.\n19\t\n20\tThe ledger itself never summarizes, ranks, or interprets. It stores what was\n21\tvisibly said, by whom, against which commit — nothing more.\n22\t\n23\t## Install\n24\t\n25\t```sh\n26\tgit clone https://github.com/evintunador/conversation-ledger\n27\tcd conversation-ledger && npm install && npm link   # npm publish coming later\n28\tcledger install all    # hook capture into Claude Code + Codex CLI\n29\t```\n30\t\n31\t`cledger install` adds `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks to `~/.claude/settings.json`\n32\tand a `Stop` hook (plus `features.hooks = true`) to `~/.codex/config.toml`,\n33\tbacking both up first. From then on, every completed turn in any git\n34\trepository is captured automatically, in the same universal format. Capture is\n35\tidempotent — events are content-derived, so re-scanning a transcript never\n36\tduplicates.\n37\t\n38\tTwo one-time activation notes: Claude Code reads hooks at session start, so\n39\tcapture begins with your next session; Codex requires you to trust new hooks\n40\tinteractively — open `codex`, run `/hooks`, and approve the `cledger hook\n41\tcodex` command once. Missed turns are never lost either way: `cledger capture\n42\t<source> --transcript PATH` backfills any native transcript, idempotently.\n43\t\n44\t## Use\n45\t\n46\t```sh\n47\tcledger log                     # events on the current branch (via commit reachability)\n48\tcledger log --all --json        # every event, as JSONL for jq & friends\n49\tcledger conversations           # sessions touching this branch\n50\tcledger show claude-code:3f9a   # replay one conversation in order\n51\tcledger export > ledger.jsonl   # lossless dump, incl. source-native payloads\n52\tcledger sync                    # explicit fetch/merge/push of the ledger ref\n53\techo '{\"kind\":\"decision\",...}' | cledger append   # any tool can write events\n54\t```\n55\t\n56\t## Sharing (transport)\n57\t\n58\tThe ledger travels with normal git use, no extra commands:\n59\t\n60\t- **Push**: the first capture in a repo installs a `pre-push` hook (chaining\n61\t  safely onto any existing shell hook; backing off with a warning when\n62\t  `core.hooksPath`/husky owns the hooks). On `git push` it pushes the ledger\n63\t  ref alongside, gated by the secret scan. A finding holds back **only the\n64\t  ledger** — your code push proceeds — unless you opt into\n65\t  `{\"transport\": {\"strict\": true}}`, which aborts the whole push.\n66\t- **Fetch**: the same first capture adds a fetch refspec on `origin`, so\n67\t  `git fetch`/`git pull` stages teammates' events; any read command\n68\t  (`cledger log`, `show`, ...) folds them in via the conflict-free\n69\t  `cat_sort_uniq` union. The local ref is never force-overwritten.\n70\t- **Opting out**: `{\"transport\": {\"hook\": false, \"fetchRefspec\": false}}` in\n71\t  `.cledger.json` or `~/.config/cledger/config.json`, or just delete the\n72\t  marked block from `.git/hooks/pre-push`. `cledger sync` always works\n73\t  explicitly either way.\n74\t\n75\tIf git has no author identity configured (`user.email` unset), human turns\n76\tare recorded unattributed; `cledger install` warns about this. cledger uses\n77\tthe same identity a commit would be authored under (config or environment)\n78\tand never guesses a hostname-based one.\n79\t\n80\t## Adapters\n81\t\n82\tSupported today (built-in, hook-based, per-turn):\n83\t\n84\t| Source | Trigger | Transcript store | Notes |\n85\t|---|---|---|---|\n86\t| Claude Code CLI | `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks | `~/.claude/projects/*/*.jsonl` | Also covers the VS Code extension and JetBrains plugin (both share `~/.claude/settings.json` hooks and transcripts), and desktop-app local/SSH/WSL sessions. Cloud \"Remote\" sessions and the Cowork tab run server-side — not captured. |\n87\t| Codex CLI | `[[hooks.Stop]]` hooks engine | `~/.codex/sessions/**/rollout-*.jsonl` | Same config + session store is shared by the Codex desktop app and IDE extension, so their local sessions should capture too — but OpenAI has open bugs on the desktop app's config loading, and third-party reports say hooks may not fire from IDE sessions. Treat non-CLI surfaces as best-effort; `cledger capture codex` backfills any rollout file regardless of which surface wrote it. Cloud tasks run server-side — not captured. Inter-agent messages (`agent_message`) are captured with their visible text; their encrypted blocks are never stored, same policy as reasoning. |\n88\t\n89\tTODO adapters, roughly in order of how ledger-friendly their storage/hook\n90\tstory looks (all have local session stores; most grew Claude-Code-style hook\n91\tsystems):\n92\t\n93\t- **Gemini CLI** — JSON chats under `~/.gemini/tmp/<hash>/chats/`; documented hooks.\n94\t- **Kimi CLI** — `~/.kimi-code/` sessions; Claude-Code-inspired lifecycle hooks.\n95\t- **GitHub Copilot CLI** — `~/.copilot/session-state/`; documented hooks dirs.\n96\t- **Factory droid** — `~/.factory/` sessions; `hooks.json`.\n97\t- **Qwen Code** — `~/.qwen/projects/*/chats/`; hooks system.\n98\t- **opencode** — SQLite under `~/.local/share/opencode/`; plugin-API events rather than shell hooks.\n99\t- **Cursor (`cursor-agent` CLI)** — `~/.cursor/chats`; hooks exist, but IDE-side chats live in editor-internal storage.\n100\t- **aider** — plain `.aider.chat.history.md`; no hook mechanism found, would need file watching.\n101\t- **Goose / Amp** — SQLite store / cloud-synced threads; hook stories unclear or absent.\n102\t\n103\t## Security & redaction\n104\t\n105\tVisible tool output can contain secrets: API keys in error messages, credentials in logs, etc. The trust boundary is transport — native transcripts are plaintext locally, so redaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. Once content reaches a note, removal is expensive, so prevention runs first at capture, with the last checkpoint at sync.\n106\t\n107\t### Redaction layers\n108\t\n109\t**Capture-time redaction** (default on): Replaces prefixed tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`, `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private keys, JWTs with `[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]`. Conservative, near-zero false-positive ruleset applied before event ids are computed.\n110\t- Threat addressed: API tokens and private keys in tool output land in shared history.\n111\t- Cost of disabling: `.cledger.json` `{\"redact\": {\"capture\": false}}` — every secret lands verbatim.\n112\t\n113\t**Custom patterns**: Extend capture rules via `{\"redact\": {\"patterns\": [{\"id\": \"my-rule\", \"pattern\": \"...\"}]}}` in `~/.config/cledger/config.json` (global) or `<repo>/.cledger.json` (repo wins).\n114\t- Threat addressed: domain-specific secrets unmatched by standard rules.\n115\t- Cost: manual configuration required.\n116\t\n117\t**Env-value masking** (opt-in, default off): Scrub exact values of environment variables and `.env` entries via `{\"redact\": {\"env\": true}}`.\n118\t- Threat addressed: unstructured secrets in local config.\n119\t- Cost of enabling: `.env` plain-config values get masked too; machine-dependent (rescans produce duplicate events with different ids).\n120\t\n121\t**Sync-time scan** (default on, tiered): Before any push, scans only new events with medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run, keyword assignments like `password=`, URL credentials). Findings abort the ledger push with a report and remediation instructions; in the pre-push hook, a finding holds back only the ledger and lets your code push proceed unless `{\"transport\": {\"strict\": true}}`.\n122\t- Threat addressed: secrets from older capture rules or new tool formats slipping through.\n123\t- Cost of disabling: `{\"scan\": {\"tier\": \"off\"}}` — secrets in tool output push silently.\n124\t- Remediation paths: `cledger redact <event-id>` (real secrets), `cledger allow <fingerprint>` (false positives), `cledger sync --no-scan` (bypass once). `--paranoid` tier adds entropy-based detection (noisier but broader).\n125\t\n126\t### Commands\n127\t\n128\t`cledger redact <event-id> (--pattern REGEX | --all) [--reason TEXT]`: Rewrites stored event to placeholder + audit metadata, appends a `redaction` event, and squashes local notes history so prior content is unrecoverable (pre-push only; post-push purge tooling is planned, not yet built).\n129\t\n130\t`cledger scan [--paranoid]`: Standalone check with exit 1 on findings — CI-friendly.\n131\t\n132\t### Maximum safety recipe\n133\t\n134\tKeep all defaults (capture and sync scan on), add repo-specific patterns in `.cledger.json` for domain-specific secrets, enable env masking only if `.env` holds secrets (not config), run `cledger scan` in CI, and treat `--no-scan` as a deliberate exception you document.\n135\t\n136\t## Roadmap\n137\t\n138\t- **Path-based capture exclusion** — the path half of the redaction config\n139\t  (\"never record reads of `secrets/**`\"); requires correlating `tool_use`\n140\t  file paths with their `tool_result` events.\n141\t- **Post-push purge** — true content removal after the ledger ref has been\n142\t  shared (force-push + collaborator re-fetch coordination); the local\n143\t  pre-push squash shipped with `cledger redact`.\n144\t- **`re-anchor`** — reattach events orphaned by squash merges or history\n145\t  rewrites. The desired end state is that this happens by default: a squash\n146\t  commit should end up carrying the conversations of the branch it squashed.\n147\t  Hard part: squashes often happen off-machine (GitHub \"Squash and merge\"),\n148\t  so detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local\n149\t  hook.\n150\t- **Harness-artifact capture** — decide whether the ledger should also\n151\t  preserve valuable non-git-controlled agent artifacts that normally die\n152\t  with a worktree or live outside the repo (e.g. Claude Code auto-memory\n153\t  directories, session state). They fit the `document` kind; the question is\n154\t  scope and capture triggers.\n155\t- **Format-drift: re-normalization** — unrecognized transcript line types are\n156\t  detected (0.4.0), preserved raw-only as `unrecognized` events rather than\n157\t  dropped (0.5.0), and now re-normalizable (0.6.0): `cledger renormalize`\n158\t  re-feeds each preserved line's `raw.data` through its owning adapter's\n159\t  current convert path and, for the ones this version can now interpret,\n160\t  appends the proper `conversation_turn` plus a `supersession` event linking\n161\t  it to the raw placeholder. The turn is reconstructed with the exact id a\n162\t  live capture would produce (same seq/session/timestamp handling), so a later\n163\t  live capture of the same session dedups rather than duplicating; the run is\n164\t  append-only and idempotent. *Remaining:* this is a manual command —\n165\t  auto-running it after an adapter/version bump on capture is deferred\n166\t  (detecting \"the adapter changed\" is its own problem).\n167\t- **Close the capture/scan-tier gap (redaction feedback loop)** — the pre-push\n168\t  scan (broad) can flag a value the capture-tier redaction (conservative) let\n169\t  through. When the flagged content sits in a *conversation about* secrets,\n170\t  the sessions spent fixing it are themselves captured, re-ingesting the same\n171\t  raw value into new events that the next scan flags again — a feedback loop.\n172\t  Allowlisting escapes it (fingerprint-keyed, so it neutralizes every\n173\t  recurrence at once), but *redaction* does not: it scrubs per-event and can't\n174\t  stop the value being re-captured, so a naive fix-sync-fix cycle can churn\n175\t  indefinitely. The structural fix is to make capture-tier coverage a superset\n176\t  of scan-tier — anything that would *block* a sync must also be *redacted at\n177\t  ingest* — so nothing scan-blockable can ever be captured raw and the loop is\n178\t  impossible by construction. Cheap first step: feed allowlisted / known-secret\n179\t  fingerprints back into capture-time redaction so known values are scrubbed on\n180\t  the way in. A second cheap step closes the loop's *sync-report* channel\n181\t  specifically: the scan/sync failure output should mask the matched span\n182\t  itself (`...config says <redacted> fine...`, context only) instead of the\n183\t  current elided-middle form that still prints the value's leading/trailing\n184\t  characters — so the report shows zero secret characters and can't seed the\n185\t  next finding when it is itself captured. Nothing is lost operationally:\n186\t  `cledger allow` keys on the fingerprint and `cledger redact` on the event id,\n187\t  neither of which needs the value visible.\n188\t- **Purge tooling** — true content removal behind a `redaction` event.\n189\t- **Sub-turn citation anchors** for downstream consumers like intent-recall.\n190\t\n191\t## Storage model, in one paragraph\n192\t\n193\tOne git note per anchor commit under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`; the\n194\tnote body is one canonical-JSON event per line, sorted and unique, with all\n195\tcontent inline (GC-safe, no out-of-repo pointers). Concurrent branches merge\n196\tconflict-free via git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes strategy. Events record\n197\trepository, branch, HEAD, dirty-tree fingerprint, actor, timestamps, and\n198\tcapture mechanism. Redaction appends a `redaction` event rather than silently\n199\trewriting history. See [docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md](docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md)\n200\tfor details and [docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md](docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md) for what this\n201\ttool deliberately refuses to become.\n202\t\n203\t## License\n204\t\n205\t[MIT](LICENSE)\n206\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_0142A863pSCXwg9ds4VdzHMu","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"5dbf0730060901fd560a1b52c3f4d24468d5d92d","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","seq":14},"id":"ev1-fa2f1a268f85e94389605bdd1b801ac191ca6e92fa57210949a82039ded15a7c","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T19:09:22.110Z","producer":{"session_id":"48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.6.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"content":"1\t# Conversation Ledger\n2\t\n3\tDurable, attributable records of visible coding-agent conversations, stored in\n4\tyour repository as git notes.\n5\t\n6\t`cledger` (also installed as `conversation-ledger`) is a small standalone\n7\tutility in the unix tradition: it appends immutable JSONL evidence events to\n8\t`refs/notes/conversation-ledger`, anchored to the commit you were on when the\n9\tco