{"actor":{"id":"claude-opus-4-8","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Good — those answers sharpen it a lot. Here's the remap, then the plan.\n\n## How your answers remap B / narrow-A / skip-C\n\n- **B (fully mask the warning): unchanged — still in.** Trivial and safe.\n- **Narrow-A (auto-scrub confirmed secrets): promoted from \"optional maybe\" to the centerpiece, on by default.** Your #2 (this bites LLM-heavy programmers a lot) is the reason to keep it, and your #3 tells me exactly *how*: the tool remembers a confirmed secret's actual value in a **local file that git structurally never sees**, and scrubs it automatically from then on.\n- **Skip-C: still skip — and now it's a principle, not just a risk call.** You said the default should *not* be to silently do aggressive things people don't expect. C is exactly that (making the cautious front-net aggressive → silently mangling innocent text). And B + narrow-A already close *both* ways the loop feeds itself, so C would only buy you the sliver of time before you've dealt with a given secret even once. Not worth violating the conservative-default principle you just stated.\n\nOne reconciliation on your #3, since it reads as a slight contradiction (\"default should be to *not* do this\" vs \"keep it on by default\"): what you don't want is secrets landing somewhere **shared or surprising**. The store I'm proposing lives inside `.git/` — which git never tracks or pushes at all (stronger than a `.gitignore` entry; it's simply not part of the repo). So *on-by-default* and *no surprising new shared location* are both satisfied. That's the whole trick.\n\n## The plan\n\n**Deliverable 1 — Fully mask the scan/sync warnings (Part B)**\n- `src/redact/scan.ts`: `buildExcerpt`/`maskMatch` currently print the secret's first-6 + `…` + last-4. Change to context-only with the secret replaced by a neutral marker (`…config token was <redacted> in the reply…`), zero secret characters. Findings are still identified by rule + fingerprint (unchanged), so nothing operational is lost.\n- Tests in `src/test/` asserting no secret substring survives in `formatFinding` output.\n\n**Deliverable 2 — Remember confirmed secrets and auto-scrub them (narrow-A)**\n- **New local store:** `.git/conversation-ledger/known-secrets.json`, sitting right next to the existing `allowlist.json`. Holds the plaintext values (with a `>= 8` char guard so short/common strings can't over-match). It's the same \"local, rebuildable, never-the-record-of-truth\" tier as the allowlist and never leaves your machine.\n- **Write path:** when you run `cledger redact <id> --pattern <regex>` (the exact case where you're telling the tool \"Net 2 caught a real secret Net 1 missed\"), capture the matched plaintext into that store. The `--all` path won't feed it (it blanks whole content, so there's no reusable value). Auto-redactions the front-net already makes are out of scope — they're already caught by their own rules.\n- **Read path:** capture-time redaction (`src/store.ts` around line 151, via `redactDraft`) already supports exact-value scrubbing — that's the `extraValues` mechanism env-masking uses. I'll load the known-secrets store and pass its values in under a `known-secret` rule id. Small, reuses existing machinery.\n- **Config:** on by default; opt-out via `.cledger.json` `{\"redact\": {\"knownSecrets\": false}}`, mirroring the other layers.\n\n**Deliverable 3 — small cleanups (your #4)**\n- Fix the README's Part-A wording (it says \"allowlisted,\" which means *confirmed-safe* — the opposite; it should read confirmed-**secret**).\n- Merge the duplicate \"Purge tooling\" / \"Post-push purge\" bullets.\n- Rewrite the roadmap bullet to describe what actually shipped.\n\n**Two honest caveats I'll also note in the README:**\n1. The known-secrets store *is* a new place a plaintext secret now lives — local-only and git-invisible, but real. You've okayed this; I just won't let it be silent in the docs.\n2. Turning this on makes capture slightly *machine-dependent* for those values (a teammate without the value in their store captures the same line unredacted → different event id). This is the identical caveat env-masking already carries; I'll group it with that one, not invent a new warning.\n\n**Sequence:** Deliverable 1 first (isolated, low-risk), then 2 (the real work), then 3 (docs). Roughly a handful of focused commits with tests alongside each.\n\nWant me to go ahead and build this, or adjust scope first? If you're good with it, I'll start on Deliverable 1.","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"5dbf0730060901fd560a1b52c3f4d24468d5d92d","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","seq":91},"id":"ev1-b6ad03e7264117661d9dfdf23d7970c88ad84072d3c7e270c208b19a121b60a2","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T21:38:16.613Z","producer":{"session_id":"48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.6.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","effort":"high","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"text":"Good — those answers sharpen it a lot. Here's the remap, then the plan.\n\n## How your answers remap B / narrow-A / skip-C\n\n- **B (fully mask the warning): unchanged — still in.** Trivial and safe.\n- **Narrow-A (auto-scrub confirmed secrets): promoted from \"optional maybe\" to the centerpiece, on by default.** Your #2 (this bites LLM-heavy programmers a lot) is the reason to keep it, and your #3 tells me exactly *how*: the tool remembers a confirmed secret's actual value in a **local file that git structurally never sees**, and scrubs it automatically from then on.\n- **Skip-C: still skip — and now it's a principle, not just a risk call.** You said the default should *n