ctly feeds the scanner's suppression. **Assumption I'm making:** you want capture to learn from confirmed *real* secrets only. Worth your explicit confirmation because the prose says the opposite.\n\n**2. \"Capture-tier as a superset of scan-tier\" contradicts the invariant the whole design rests on.** `rules.ts` is explicit: capture rules must be near-zero-false-positive *because a capture false positive silently rewrites the record*, while scan-tier is allowed to be noisy *because it only warns a human*. Standard-tier (`password=…`, url-creds, bearer) and especially the paranoid entropy rule (`[A-Za-z0-9+/_=-]{24,}`) are deliberately noisy. Promoting them to run at capture means silently, irreversibly rewriting records on every base64 blob, hash, or long ID. Taken literally, \"anything scan-blockable must be redacted at ingest\" trades a reviewable warning for a silent mutation — the exact thing the design avoids. **My read of what you probably want** is the narrower, value-based version: capture learns the *specific confirmed secret values* (step A), so nothing you've *already identified* can be re-captured raw — not \"run the noisy regex tiers at capture.\" Those are very different scopes and the text collapses them.\n\n**3. Fingerprints can't actually drive capture scrubbing — you need the plaintext.** A fingerprint is `sha256(value)[:12]`. Capture-time redaction works by regex/exact-string replacement (`redactExtraValues` does exact-string). You cannot scan arbitrary text for \"a substring whose hash equals fp\" without the value. So step A really requires a **local store of known-secret plaintext values** that capture does exact-string matching against — same mechanism as env masking. The natural place to capture that plaintext is *at `cledger redact` time*, when the value is still in hand. This is consistent with your stated threat model (transcripts are already plaintext locally; the boundary is transport), but it means a new local secrets file under `.git/conversation-ledger/`. **Assumption:** you're okay with that local-plaintext store; if not, step A can't exist as described.\n\nTwo smaller notes:\n- **Step B may be nearly moot.** The current excerpt breaks the value with `…`, so the regex rules (min-length, no ellipsis) mostly won't re-match it, and the paranoid rule needs 24+ contiguous chars. So the loop is *already* mostly closed for the report channel. Full-masking is cheap belt-and-suspenders, but it costs the human affordance of recognizing *which* secret at a glance. Minor.\n- **\"Purge tooling\" duplicates \"Post-push purge\"** higher in the list — both are \"true content removal behind a redaction event.\" Probably one bullet.\n\n## Clarifying questions\n\n1. Is #6 genuinely the next thing to *build*, or did you intend those two commits to park it as documented-for-later and move to something else (e.g. `re-anchor`, or the format-drift auto-run)?\n2. Do you agree step A should key on **redacted (real-secret)** values, not the allowlist — and are you okay with a **local plaintext known-secrets store** (populated at `redact` time) as the mechanism, since fingerprints alone can't scrub?\n3. For the \"structural fix\": do you actually want the **narrow value-based** superset (capture knows confirmed secrets), or did you truly mean promoting the noisy scan *rule tiers* to capture — accepting silent rewrites on false positives?\n4. How real is this loop for you in practice? It only fires when the *raw secret value* re-appears in tool output during a fix session — the `redact`/`allow` commands themselves never need it typed. If it's rare, step B alone may be enough and the structural fix isn't worth the risk.\n5. Should I fold \"Purge tooling\" and \"Post-push purge\" into one bullet?\n\nWant me to answer any of these myself where a sensible default exists, or would you rather work through them?","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversati